data.description:
In GLSL, vector data types have a functionality called [*swizzling*](https://www.khronos.org/opengl/wiki/Data_Type_(GLSL)#Swizzling). A vector is an array with length 2, 3 or 4. Swizzling allows the programmer to access elements of the vector using the following syntax.

```
// vector initialization
vec4 col = vec4(0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4);

// a is a copy of col
vec4 a = col.xyzw;

// individual elements can be accessed, b is 0.1
float b = col.x; 

// vectors can be accessed like arrays, c is 0.1
float c = col[0];

// elements can be reordered and repeated by swizzling, d is vec3(0.2, 0.1, 0.1)
vec3 d = col.yxx;

// swizzled elements can be set, d is now vec3(0.2, 0.6, 0.5)
d.zy = vec2(0.5, 0.6);

// elements can't be repeated when being set, d[0] is still 0.2
d.xxx = vec3(0.7, 0.8, 0.9);

// there are three different swizzle masks - xyzw, rgba and stpq are equivalent
vec4 e = col.rgba;
vec4 f = col.stpq;

// swizzle masks can't be mixed, treat this like a normal property
vec3 notSupported = col.wat;

// swizzle masks must be 1 to 4 characters long, treat longer masks like normal properties
vec8 alsoNotSupported = col.rrggbbaa;
```

Let's recreate this handy functionality.
